{
  "text": "It has been suggested the carbon used to build the inducedreaction zones originates directly from current assimilates [CITATION_1] . Stored compounds accumulated in various tissues, such as inner bark around the induced-reaction zones or other tissues, may also be mobilized. Indeed, a decrease of soluble sugars and lipids in the phloem was observed as a consequence of construction of the induced-reaction zones [CITATION_2] . The ability of trees to stop bark beetle attacks may be correlated with the level of soluble carbohydrates around attack points [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Carbon used to build-up the induced-reaction zones may also originate from starch hydrolysis around the attack points [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . In fact, starch decreased in the phloem of Picea abies after mass inoculation with Ceratocystis polonica, but no correlation was found between starch concentration in the phloem and tree resistance [CITATION_7] . During mass attacks, available carbohydrates may be consumed rapidly and subsequent transport of soluble sugars from needles is required [CITATION_8] .",
  "citation_candidates": [
